John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have a number of academic successes and this continues in 2018 with other excellent test results. Individual and group successes in sporting, artistic, musical and other community activities only underline this.
These schools have more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) and strive to provide their pupils and parents with the best possible level of service.
Independent schools prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement individually tailored school education plans, we observe that modern languages are still popular and sought-after subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is important to note that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely solely on English.
The latest results of this year’s exams show that languages are at the top of the charts, with the highest success rate being independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who learned a foreign language achieved the best A grade.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that the highest grade A reached 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by students are as important in the study plans of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17 per cent of job vacancies are under-skilled due to reasons employers report as problems.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
Given that more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalised world. -
No matter what career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have the real advantage of having such a lifelong skill in the future.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, with a single language spoken by a two-digit 15% French, specifically.
That is why it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially the languages of the developing economies, they will be more likely to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school is different in the way it teaches languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 outlook, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child is interested in, he will always have at independent schools to choose from several languages with teachers who are experts in the given field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that languages are essential for the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should, in fact, be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and landmark to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
