The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this only now, in my last year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was presented for the first time this year, explains students basic information about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university decided to introduce a course after finding that the students were really seriously sleepy during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part is the picture of student colleges where students click on cups with coffee, curtains, tennis and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In other parts, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
The interactive icon map of the campus then invites participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “studying all night” still exists, he added, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is also growing.
Enough good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even so that it doesn't get accumulating, because sleep deprivation switches the brain to starvation mode, so the person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that took one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
