Red tide update: Concentrations drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota districts
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission points to the overall decline in red tidal concentrations in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC report, spots of flowering water are now reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – this indicates a declining concentration.
The flowering waters of the red tide range about 130 miles of coastline from the northern district of Pinellas to the southern district of Lee.
The spots were observed about 10 miles off the coast in Hillsborough County, but last week there were relatively fewer places.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, the average concentrations of voles at the coast or at the open sea in the Pinellas district were reported at the voles. In the Hillsborough district, low to high concentrations were observed in the open sea, at the low to high concentrations at the low to high concentrations, at the low to high concentrations at the sea level in the Manatee district, and at the lowest concentrations at the high concentrations at the Saratee district.
Respiratory irritation continues to occur in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
Inflammation of the airways was not reported in northwest Florida last week.
